Project Foundations for Data Science: FoodHub Data Analysis¶

Marks: 60

Context¶

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective¶

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary¶

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

A. Cuisine vs Cost of the order

In [26]:
# Ordering the cuisine types by median values
order_A = df.groupby('cuisine_type')['cost_of_the_order'].median().sort_values().index

# Relationship between cost of the order and cuisine type
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 8))
sns.boxplot(data=df, x='cuisine_type', y='cost_of_the_order', order=order_A)
plt.xlabel('Cuisine Type', size=13)
plt.ylabel('Cost of the order (dollar)', size=13)
plt.xticks(rotation=60)
plt.show()
  • Vietnamese and Korean cuisines have the lowest order costs compared to other cuisines. These two cuisines also have their order costs condensed.
  • French and Thai cuisine are the most expensive cuisines median. However, French cuisine has the most expensive order cost with a median around 20 dollars.
  • We can also see that 4 cuisines have similar boxplots indicating that their quartile costs are similar. These cuisines are Japanese, American, Italian, and Chinese.
  • Outliers are present in this graph for Korean, Mediterranean, and Vietnamese cuisines. This indicated that they had some extreme order costs.

  • However, the true value of the order cost varie less than 1 dollars in regards to the rating, meaning that cost of the order may not play a role in ratings.

Question 14: The company charges the restaurant 25% on the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars and 15% on the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars. Find the net revenue generated by the company across all orders. [3 marks]¶

In [47]:
# Creating a function (calculate_rev) to get the company's revenue on each order thanks to a loop
def calculate_rev(x):
    if x > 20:              # Order(x) greater than 20 dollars
        return x * 0.25     # Multiply the order cost by 25 %
    elif x > 5:             # Order(x) greater than 5 dollars
        return x * 0.15     # Multiply the order cost by 15 %
    else:
        return x * 0        # Multiply the order cost by 0 if the order cost is lower than 5 dollars.

# Creating a new column 'revenue' in our dataframe (df) with the company's revenue corresponding each order
df['revenue'] = df['cost_of_the_order'].apply(calculate_rev)
df.head()

Conclusion and Recommendations¶

Question 17: What are your conclusions from the analysis? What recommendations would you like to share to help improve the business? (You can use cuisine type and feedback ratings to drive your business recommendations.) [6 marks]¶

Conclusions:¶

  • Out of 1898 orders, almost 39% have not been rated.
  • The rating of the orders seems to be related to the delivery time as 3 star reviews are due to higher delivery times.
  • There are no rating under 3 stars.
  • FoodHub reveives more than double the orders during the weekend compared to weekdays.
  • Delivery time is higher during weekdays and this could be due to a higher traffic volume during those days or less delivery persons by lower demands.
  • Almost 11% of their total delivery time are over 60 minutes.
  • The most popular restaurant is Shake Shack with the highest received orders (219).
  • Around 83% of the orders are Japanese, American, Italian, and Chinese cuisines. These four cuisines seems to be the most popular among the customers on FoodHub.
  • However, the most population cuisine is American

Recommendations:¶

  • FoodHub company should look in the reason behind the high amount of not given rating as customers rating is an important factor not only to gauge customer statisfaction but also for other customers to chose which restaurant to order from. The rating page on the app probably needs to be modifed and upgraded to get a higher rating number.

  • As the weekdays delivery times are higher, the company should maybe change their mean of transportation to motobikes or bikecycles to help reduce time being stuck in traffic.

  • The company should look into employing more delivery persons during weekdays to reduce the delivery time to see if it has an impact on total revenues. In other words, is there a correlation between the reduction of the delivery time and the number of orders. Are the orders going to increase during weekdays because of a lower delivery time in order to get a high revenue?

  • In addtion to changing their mean of transportation and increasing employement during weendays, FoodHUb could also implement a maximum delivery time and offer a reward or bonus to all punctual delivery persons. This factor could also have a positive effect on delivery time.

  • FoodHub should also provide promotional offers the top 3 rated-restaurants and the top 3 restaurant with the highest order count. These offers could increse the number of orders received by those restaurants and it would be a beneficial gain for both businesses.

  • As the most popular cuisines are American, Japanese, Italian, and Chinese, Foodhub could recruite more restaurants with these types of cuisines to increase orders and revenue.

  • If, this company would like to keep some of the lowest cuisine type such as Korean or Vietnamese, they could create advertisement/promote on those cuisines to encourage customers to order. They could also offer some type of discounts for those cuisines in the begening to increase rating on those types of cuisine.

  • Since FoodHub is getting a percentage of the order cost, they could increase the number of restaurant in French and Southern cuisine as they have a heiger mean order cost.
